Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry all produce. Halve and peel @yellow onion{1}; finely chop one half (save the other half for another use). Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Trim and quarter @zucchini{1} lengthwise; thinly slice crosswise.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, @Tuscan Heat Spice{1/2%tsp}, and @water{1/4%cup}. (For 4 servings, use 1 tsp Tuscan Heat Spice and ½ cup water.) Let sit until water has mostly absorbed, ~{2-3%minutes}, then add @ground beef{10%oz}, half the @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, @garlic{1/2%tsp} (¾ tsp for 4), @salt{1/2%tsp} (1 tsp for 4) and @pepper{}. Gently combine, then form into 10-12 meatballs (20-24 for 4).

Lightly coat a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{}. Place meatballs on prepared sheet. Bake on top rack until browned, ~{12-15%minutes} (they'll finish cooking in step 5).

Meanwhile, heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add chopped onion and a big pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{4-6%minutes}. Add zucchini and remaining garlic. Season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until zucchini is tender and lightly browned, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%oz} to pot. Cook until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}, then drain and set aside. To pan with veggies, add @marinara cup{1%14oz}, @water{1/4%cup}, remaining @Tuscan Heat Spice{1/2%tsp}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} (1 tsp for 4 servings), salt, and pepper. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to medium. Cook until slightly thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}. Stir in meatballs. Cook until sauce is very thick and meatballs are cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} more.

Return spaghetti to empty pot. Carefully pour in sauce, including meatballs, and @butter{2%tbsp}; toss to coat. If sauce seems dry, add a splash or two of water. Season with salt and pepper. Divide between plates and sprinkle with remaining Parmesan.

> Just say when! This dish is finished with a big sprinkling of Parm for a deliciously autentico experience.